<DOC><DOCNO> AP890619-0292 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 2007EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-EEC-Stocks     06-19 0119</FIRST><SECOND>AM-EEC-Stocks,0125</SECOND><HEAD>EEC Ministers Adopt Ban On Insider Trading</HEAD><DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   EEC ministers Monday agreed to ban insidertrading on European stock exchanges over the next three years.   The decision will require some of the 12 countries in theEuropean Economic Community, including Germany, Italy, Belgium andIreland, to tighten their rules regarding trading on insiderinformation.   Insider trading is defined by the EEC as the use of privilegedinformation for personal gain. Privileged information is informationthat has not been revealed to the public and could influence theprice of a stock if it were.   Under the proposal, all EEC countries must enact measures``sufficiently strong'' to prevent insider trading no later thanJune 1, 1992.</TEXT></DOC>